Tangents and intersections with circles

A straight line and circle can have two, one or no points of intersection.

 

 

For a given circle in the plane we can describe any line as:

  • external if it does not meet the circle.
  • a tangent if it touches the circle at one point.
  • secant if it cuts the circle at two points.

For any point \(P\) on the circle, there is a unique tangent which passes through \(P\) called the tangent at P. For any external point \(A\) there are exactly two tangents called the external tangents from A. We can see this in the diagram below.

 


To find out how many times a line and circle meet, we can use substitution. To show that a line is a tangent to a circle, the equation of the line can be substituted into the equation of the circle, and solved – there should only be one solution.
